4 Genetic biomarkers
4.1 Genetics
Cohort studies by Sidransky et al. showed that PD patients carrying the heterozygous GBA N370S mutation have a 2.8-fold increased risk of developing MCI compared to non-carriers, with L444P mutation carriers exhibiting an even higher risk (
50
). Polymeropoulos et al. found that 80% of PD patients carrying the SNCA A53T mutation progressed to MCI within 3 years after diagnosis, significantly higher than non-carriers (
51
). Kiely et al. reported that the SNCA E46K mutation accelerates α -synuclein fibril formation, which is associated with temporal cortical atrophy and memory impairment (
52
). Irwin et al. found that PD-MCI patients carrying APOE ε 4 exhibit significantly elevated cerebrospinal fluid p-tau181 levels, indicating aggravated tau pathology (
53
). Zhang et al.'s fMRI study showed that the Val/Val genotype weakens functional connectivity between the DLPFC and the striatum, exacerbating deficits in cognitive flexibility (
54
).

